const mountBtn = document.createElement('button');
mountBtn.textContent = 'Mount 4 GB GGUF';
mountBtn.onclick = async () => {
  const [handle] = await window.showOpenFilePicker({
    types: [{description: 'GGUF model', accept: {'application/octet-stream': ['.gguf']}}]
  });
  llamaWorker.postMessage({cmd: 'load', fileHandle: handle});
};
document.getElementById('header-bar').appendChild(mountBtn);
```

--------------------------------------------------------
What happens
--------------------------------------------------------
1. User clicks **“Mount 4 GB GGUF”** – no file copy, no size limit.  
2. Worker **memory-maps** the handle directly into **llama.cpp WASMFS**.  
3. **WebGPU** backend streams **4-bit** tokens back to the chat pane.  
4. Everything else (Monaco, Rawr tracing, GPU spoofer) stays **untouched**.

--------------------------------------------------------
Still one file?
--------------------------------------------------------
Yes – just replace the **old worker blob** with the new one above and drop the **base64 string** (you’ll generate it once) in place of `%LLAMA_WASM_GZ_B64%`.  
Total page weight **< 1 MB** until the user picks their 4.7 GB model – **no wrap, no Electron, no server**.

Enjoy your **browser-native, 4 GB+ LLM IDE**.'

